nt communicative artifacts, designs, and contexts; while attending to their immersive, aesthetic, and ideological dimensions. Each contribution details innovative aspects of empirical multimodality research, offering insights into challenges evolving from quantitative approaches, particular corpus work, results from eye-tracking and psychological experiments, and analyses of dynamic interactive experiences. The approaches and results presented foreground the inherent multidisciplinary nature and implications of multimodality, renegotiating concepts across linguistics, media studies, (social) semiotics, game studies, and design. With this, the volume will inform both current and future developments in theory, methods, and transdisciplinary contexts and become a landmark reference for anyone interested in the empirical study of multimodality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aDigital Humanities. 4aEmpirie. 4aKorpusanalyse. 4aMultimodalität.  acorpus analysis.  adigital humanities.  aempiricism.  amultimodality.1 aBateman, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateman, John A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoesen, Kristoffer Claussen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwerth, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiippala, Tuomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiang, Zhanhao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohannessen, Christian Mosbæk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKang, Jiaping, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessell, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiaer, Jieun, econtributor.